<TITLE> Human chain formed to save rivers </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 05 (bdnews24.com)Youths from different non-governmental institutes formed a human chain in front of the National Press Club demanding steps to free the rivers, especailly Buriganga, Shitalakhya, Turag and Balu, of encroachment and pollution. The programme was arranged by Green Voice, a youth forum working on environmental issues. They declared an eight-point charter of demand that includes activating the taskforce on Buriganga, setting up effluent treatment plants in industries, stopping untreated waste going into the river, strict implementation of Water Body Act 2000 and demolishing illegal structures along the rivers. In a rally, they demanded tough government measures to save the rivers. Public health and the ecology will continue to suffer if the rivers were not back to their previous state, they observed. Shahidullah Chowdhury, convener of the National Committee to Protect Oil-Gas-Mineral Resources and Electricity-Port; Dr Noor Uddin, executive director of NGO Seba; Nazmul Karim, programme manager of WBB Trust; Mihir Biswas, member secretary of Save Buriganga Movement; Bidhan Chandra Pal of Hunger Project; Humaun Kabir Suman, assistant coordinator of Green Voice; Zubaer Ahmed of Dhaka College, Sadiqur Rahman Nonam of Titumir College, Faisal Hossain of State University; Aminul Islam Maolana Bhashani of Teachers Training College, and Laila Ferdousi of Eden College, among others, spoke
